  <steps>
    <step order="1">Grep BFF for `SoftSlashIntentToCapabilityName` — locate exact file + line.</step>
    <step order="2">Grep frontend for `SOFT_SLASH_TO_INTENT` (or equivalent map). Located in SoftSlashRouter or similar.</step>
    <step order="3">Verify the dict's only consumers are in legacy routing path. Trace and confirm with task 115 in place, no production code depends on the dict.</step>
    <step order="4">Delete the BFF dict + any companion enum entries that exist only to support the dict.</step>
    <step order="5">Delete the frontend mapping object + any wrapper functions whose only callers were the slash→capability flow.</step>
    <step order="6">Run BFF tests `dotnet test tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/`. All pass. If any test relied on the dict, refactor to use `commandIntent` bias semantics from task 115.</step>
    <step order="7">Run frontend tests `npm test` in `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/`. All pass.</step>
    <step order="8">Run frontend build: `npm install --legacy-peer-deps --no-audit --no-fund` then `npm run build`.</step>
    <step order="9">Re-run FR-20 binding test from task 115 — slash + NL routes identically.</step>
    <step order="10">Grep prove: `grep -rn "SoftSlashIntentToCapabilityName" src/` returns zero hits; `grep -rn "SOFT_SLASH_TO_INTENT" src/` returns zero hits.</step>
    <step order="11">Measure BFF publish size; expect minor reduction.</step>
    <step order="12">code-review + adr-check (Step 9.5 quality gates).</step>
    <step order="13">Update TASK-INDEX.md: task 116 → ✅; current-task.md → update.</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="Grep">Locate dict + verify zero consumers post-delete</tool>
